WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.680
Hi, everybody. Welcome back to the Data Science Hangout. I'm Rachel Dempsey. I lead Customer

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:22.160
Marketing at Posit. Posit, if you are joining a Hangout without knowing who we are, we are

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.600
the open source data science company building tools for the individual team and enterprise.

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:32.599
Thanks so much for taking the time out of your day to hang out with us. The Hangout

00:00:32.599 --> 00:00:37.119
is our open space to hear what's going on in the world of data across different industries

00:00:37.119 --> 00:00:41.880
and to connect with others who are facing similar things as you. And we get together

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:49.759
here every Thursday at the same time, same place. We do have one week we're taking off

00:00:49.759 --> 00:00:57.119
August 15th for the week of Posit Count. And so I know I've asked this many times before,

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:02.639
but if anyone from the Hangout will be there in person, please let me know in the chat.

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:08.320
I'm trying to get some people together one of the days of the conference as well. But

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:15.760
if you want to join us virtually, you can as well. And let me, bad at multitasking here,

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.800
let me put this into the chat. If you want to register to join the conference virtually

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:25.800
too. And I always like to add, if you're watching this Hangout as a recording and you want to

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:30.680
join us live in the future, we'd love to have you join us. And there's details to add

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:37.360
it to your calendar below. Just make sure it adds it for 12 Eastern time. I know people

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:42.680
really enjoy connecting with other attendees here in the Hangout in the chat. So if you

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:48.360
want to use this time now to introduce yourself, say hello, maybe share where you're based

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:53.760
or something you like to do for fun, feel free. I love to see people connecting there

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:58.519
and making friends from the Hangout. We're all dedicated to keeping this the friendly

00:01:58.519 --> 00:02:03.680
and welcoming space that you all have made it and love hearing from you no matter your

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:08.320
years of experience, titles, the languages you work in, or the industry that you work

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:15.000
in. Another quick note, if you're hiring, you can also share those roles in the chat

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:22.179
too. But today, if you want to jump in and ask questions or provide your own perspective,

00:02:22.179 --> 00:02:26.880
you can raise your hand on Zoom. I'll call on you to jump in. You could put questions

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:32.380
in the Zoom chat and feel free to put a little asterisk or star next to it if you want me

00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:38.339
to read it. Or I could call on you to introduce yourself and add some context. And then lastly,

00:02:38.339 --> 00:02:44.320
we do have a Slido link where you could ask a question anonymously too. And I'm sure Curtis

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:51.059
will be sharing that here in the chat in just a second. But thank you all again for joining

00:02:51.100 --> 00:02:56.539
us. I'm so excited to be joined by my co-host today, Shannon Pileggi, Lead Data Scientist

00:02:56.539 --> 00:03:02.820
at the Prostate Cancer Clinical Trials Consortium. And Shannon, I'd love to have you kick us

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:07.360
off with introducing yourself, share a little bit about your role today, but also something

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:09.419
you do outside of work too.

00:03:09.419 --> 00:03:18.000
Sure. So my name is Shannon Pileggi. My background is in biostatistics. I was a college professor

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:23.960
for a few years, and I worked in market research for a few years. And more recently, I've been

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:32.119
in clinical trials for the past three years, and it's my happy place now. Outside of data

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:41.479
science, I recently got into a gym in my local town. It's a community-owned gym. I go six

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:47.500
days a week. I'm really into weightlifting. And I was thinking about it this morning,

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:53.539
and I feel like it's not entirely unlike what we do in data science, and that you're

00:03:53.539 --> 00:03:58.679
constantly pushing yourself to failure and iterating and figuring out what works and

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:00.179
moving on and getting stronger.

00:04:00.179 --> 00:04:09.300
I love that. Thank you. I also wanted to add, I know in the years that we've had the data

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:15.520
science Hangout, I've seen a lot of Shannon's blog posts recommended here in the Zoom chat

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:21.679
over the years. So I just wanted to make sure to share your blog here in the chat too.

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:23.279
Thank you.

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:30.000
But Shannon, I think just to get us started, I'd love to hear a little bit more about your

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.399
journey into data science and how you got started.

00:04:33.399 --> 00:04:40.839
Yeah, sure. I mean, being a college professor, I knew about statistics, and I knew about

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:45.760
programming, and it eventually got a little frustrating that I was sending people out

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:53.119
in the world to tackle cool programming problems, but not having any experience doing so myself.

00:04:53.119 --> 00:05:00.920
And so I was ready to make a change. And so my first industry position was more statistics-oriented.

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:07.000
And as I started doing that more, I realized I had more fun learning about the programming

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:14.959
side. And so in my current role, I am definitely more programming-focused and less statistics-focused.

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:19.040
But I would say I've been using R since about 2005.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:26.519
Awesome. Thank you. Well, I get to ask some of the questions in the beginning as we wait

00:05:26.519 --> 00:05:32.480
for them to come in from everybody. But something I was curious to ask you about, because I

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.239
saw one of your recent blog posts around working with Excel and R, and I wanted to

00:05:38.239 --> 00:05:44.959
learn a little more from you on the collaboration between data science teams and business stakeholders

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:51.239
who prefer Excel. And I was wondering if you had any tips or lessons learned for us.

00:05:51.239 --> 00:05:57.359
Yeah. I mean, a lot of what we do is we have to work with other people to put together

00:05:57.359 --> 00:06:03.880
reports. And in an ideal world, we could seam together our reproducible tables and

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:13.920
their narrative. But we're not going to onboard our partners to GitHub and teach them how

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:18.320
to use Markdown. I mean, obviously, they could learn that, but that's just not realistic

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:24.640
for where we're at. So we often do produce tables in Excel for them to paste into the

00:06:24.679 --> 00:06:28.079
reports as they need to. And it's just it's what works right now.

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:36.640
Yeah, I think the post I saw was about exporting a table.

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:44.920
Yeah. I mean, Excel is like a pretty like gnarly beast to tackle, especially like you

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:49.359
get used to like so much like really pretty formatting from GT tables and like you're

00:06:49.359 --> 00:06:53.600
like doing all these beautiful things in HTML and then you try to dump it into Excel and

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:55.559
like none of the beautiful things come out right.

00:06:56.480 --> 00:07:01.559
And so that recent post was just about some tips you can use, like intermediate workflows

00:07:01.559 --> 00:07:06.279
and steps to like make the formatting come out as close as possible to what you

00:07:06.279 --> 00:07:09.480
specified. But it's still not perfect.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:15.440
Would you actually be able to give us a few examples of some of the projects that you

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:19.320
work on in your role just to kind of put us in your everyday mindset?

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:27.559
Yeah. And so I work on clinical trials and we deal with a large amount of data.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:33.440
And so part of the work that we do is to ensure that we're getting data in a timely

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:35.679
manner and that we're getting good quality data.

00:07:36.559 --> 00:07:42.399
So we might be making monitoring reports, looking like holistically at all of the

00:07:42.399 --> 00:07:47.320
sites that are enrolling in clinical trials, like are they doing a good job and

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:48.839
entering certain fields?

00:07:48.839 --> 00:07:51.000
And does the data look like of good quality?

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And obviously we have different ways to assess that.

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:01.440
Other types of like standard reports we do are safety reports for different monitoring

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:04.920
agencies where we're looking at adverse event reporting and stuff like that.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:12.519
Thank you. I see Abigail had asked a question in the chat and I'll read it, but it

00:08:12.519 --> 00:08:17.959
was in 2005, did your employer teach you R or did you learn it yourself on the side?

00:08:17.959 --> 00:08:20.079
How did you learn about R initially?

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:23.000
Yeah, 2005, that was back in graduate school.

00:08:23.239 --> 00:08:28.679
So we definitely had graduate school courses in R and that was my first exposure.

00:08:28.679 --> 00:08:32.320
I also learned SAS when I was a college professor.

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:35.280
I taught both R and SAS programming.

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:40.479
And then when I moved into my first industry position, our team was mixed.

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:47.880
So we were R programmers and SPSS programmers and also people who are very good at

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:54.599
writing like Excel macros and like doing crazy things in Excel that I've never done

00:08:54.599 --> 00:09:01.760
before. And so I would say, you know, that job more and more started to encourage and

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:06.719
support the use of R, especially as they saw like the powerful things we could do in

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:08.039
Shiny and Connect.

00:09:11.479 --> 00:09:14.080
So far, everyone's making me read the questions.

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:21.880
I see Bill said, is there a list of packages specifically related to oncology research

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:24.840
and reporting? And that's widely used in SAS.

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:27.320
There are the standard procs and visualizations.

00:09:27.679 --> 00:09:32.320
What would be the basic toolkit for reporting the results of a cancer trial to a

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:33.520
regulatory agency?

00:09:33.719 --> 00:09:36.159
My basic toolkit is GT summary.

00:09:36.159 --> 00:09:39.119
It's my favorite package for making tables.

00:09:39.159 --> 00:09:43.359
I think it's flexible and can do pretty much everything you need it to do.

00:09:43.359 --> 00:09:47.599
And our bread and butter in reporting of trials is tables.

00:09:51.719 --> 00:09:54.960
Shannon, I know you're really involved in the community.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:59.159
I think that's very clear from all the ways you're going to be involved in the POSIT

00:09:59.159 --> 00:10:04.840
conference, as well as I thought you were at USAR and you're involved with RLadies.

00:10:05.239 --> 00:10:11.520
I'd love to just hear a little bit about that and how you got involved with the

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:15.799
community to begin with and especially RLadies leadership, too.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:21.960
Yeah, so getting involved in the community was definitely baby steps.

00:10:22.239 --> 00:10:23.799
You have to start somewhere.

00:10:23.799 --> 00:10:29.679
I think it was a little easier when Twitter existed or people were active on Twitter.

00:10:30.679 --> 00:10:36.559
And so some of the first things I did was start blogging that helped me to get to know

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:39.919
people as they gave me feedback on the blog posts.

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:46.840
Another really cool program that I enjoyed was when we were on Twitter, I served as RLadies

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:52.520
curator for Twitter, where they had a rotating person each week showcase like things that

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:57.840
they did in R. And that helped me get to know more people in the community.

00:10:58.119 --> 00:11:03.559
And through that role, I eventually joined the RLadies global team to support the Twitter

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:04.840
curation program.

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:08.119
And unfortunately, we had to retire that as we decided to leave Twitter.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:14.440
And then fairly soon after that, there was a call for volunteers to step up to join the

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:15.280
leadership team.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:23.200
And so I said, yes, and so now I've been on the leadership team for about a year and a

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:30.200
half now. And what that means is that for the RLadies organization, we are a nonprofit

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:31.840
and we have a board of directors.

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:36.200
So I am one of five individuals on the board of directors.

00:11:37.159 --> 00:11:38.119
And yeah.

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:45.679
That's awesome. I see Adam had a kind of a follow up question here when you mentioned

00:11:45.679 --> 00:11:47.520
blogging. Adam, do you want to jump in?

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:51.559
Yeah, you said the word as I was typing the question, but good to speak with you.

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:55.039
So I'm just curious about just kind of a question was how you got into blogging, which I

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:58.799
think you partially answered, but also how do you come up with the ideas for your blog

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:00.359
posts and kind of like what keeps you going?

00:12:00.359 --> 00:12:03.400
Because I know that a blog is something that I've thought about doing.

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:06.640
I'm just like, I don't even know, like, how am I going to get into it?

00:12:06.640 --> 00:12:08.479
Am I going to have enough steam to keep going?

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:18.039
Yeah, I mean, part of like I explained that that market research job had so many mixed

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:24.840
skills in terms of programming that like not everyone appreciated the cool things I was

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:26.919
doing in art. And I thought they were cool.

00:12:26.919 --> 00:12:30.440
And I kind of felt like they were just kind of sitting on a computer, like going to

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:32.919
waste. And I was like, this is the thought.

00:12:33.799 --> 00:12:36.400
So I wanted to get it out into the world.

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:41.400
And so I just had to think carefully about what I could do that was shareable or frame

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:44.159
it in a different context that was shareable.

00:12:45.799 --> 00:12:47.520
And so that's what got me started.

00:12:48.239 --> 00:12:53.960
As far as like what keeps it going, I think having an infrastructure that just works

00:12:54.239 --> 00:12:57.919
keeps it going. You know, you see a lot of people talk about like, oh, I went to go like

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:02.599
make a blog post and all of a sudden I figured out I had to like update things on my

00:13:02.599 --> 00:13:05.440
website and everything broke and I couldn't get my post out there.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:06.919
And that's like not a happy place.

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:12.320
I think a lot of like the technology has changed so that you don't have to live in that

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:13.799
unhappy place anymore.

00:13:14.479 --> 00:13:20.479
I'm like super pleased because my blog is built in Distil, which was like predated

00:13:20.479 --> 00:13:26.000
Quarto. And I always think about updating my blog to Quarto.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.080
But, you know, like every time I go back to blog, like it still works.

00:13:30.119 --> 00:13:31.400
So like why?

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:34.080
Like the infrastructure is there and it's easy.

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:38.000
And now I can put my energy into like writing a new blog post when I have the time

00:13:38.239 --> 00:13:41.880
instead of updating my actual blog infrastructure.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:48.840
As far as like the motivation to keep blogging goes, like I just kind of like writing.

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:52.919
And if I don't, if I go too long without writing, I get a little itch to start writing

00:13:52.919 --> 00:13:59.119
again. I was putting like pressure on myself when I started to have goals to like blog

00:13:59.119 --> 00:14:05.280
once a month. And now with assuming other responsibilities, especially with our

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:09.400
leadership team, those goals are like not sustainable and not realistic.

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:11.559
And so now I'm just happy when I get one out.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:16.880
Thank you, Jacob.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:18.760
I see you had a question a little bit earlier.

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:19.760
You want to jump in next?

00:14:23.159 --> 00:14:29.760
Yeah, I was just wondering if you mentioned being on the board, so do you feel like

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:34.559
it's it would be necessary to have someone at that C-suite level or like a board

00:14:34.559 --> 00:14:37.280
member or CDO in order to advance data science?

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:47.599
I mean, I guess maybe I could use a little bit more context of your question, like for

00:14:47.599 --> 00:14:51.679
the Our Ladies board of director, our mission is specifically aimed at empowering

00:14:51.679 --> 00:14:54.039
gender minorities in our spaces.

00:14:54.840 --> 00:15:01.000
We're not necessarily aimed at advancing data science, but just empowering those

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.400
voices. Oh, I misunderstood.

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:07.440
I thought you were saying that you were on the board, that you're a company.

00:15:08.479 --> 00:15:11.320
I didn't realize that was in the context of Our Ladies, sorry.

00:15:11.320 --> 00:15:12.679
Yeah, yeah, no worries.

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:21.280
Yeah, but I think that question probably still applies to like maybe at a broader

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:27.440
level, but how would you advise some of us advocating for data science in our

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:32.239
companies if we don't yet have someone at the executive level supporting it?

00:15:32.599 --> 00:15:34.559
Yeah, I think you got to get someone in the door.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:43.039
I don't know how you I think when you advocate for things in your company, like

00:15:43.039 --> 00:15:49.400
sometimes you can start small and you can start grassroots and you're like you get

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:53.520
all the people in your level and you agree that this is like the best way to move

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:56.200
forward. And like it just never happens.

00:15:56.200 --> 00:15:59.239
And then at some time, some point you just have to take it straight to the top.

00:15:59.559 --> 00:16:03.440
And if that leadership doesn't agree, then like it's just not going to happen.

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:07.640
But it's sometimes that's like the best way to get it moving instead of grassroots.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:14.200
I see there's.

00:16:16.039 --> 00:16:20.960
I'm trying to keep up with some of the questions and comments on SAS in here as

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:23.919
well, but I think it was.

00:16:26.359 --> 00:16:33.359
Rebecca, no, Elizabeth, you had a question about like pushing for our and relation to

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:36.960
SAS, you want to jump in and add context or ask about that?

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:47.000
And maybe it was partially a joke, but I see you referring to the SAS mafia.

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:58.159
But I think that maybe a broader question I can I can ask is there's a lot of people

00:16:58.159 --> 00:17:03.280
I've noticed who are joining the Hangouts who maybe are having to use SAS in their

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:08.920
roles, but wanting to start using R and what are the ways that they can.

00:17:10.040 --> 00:17:13.439
Start doing that and making the switch.

00:17:14.119 --> 00:17:20.040
Yeah, I mean, I think sometimes you have to ask like depending on where you are and do

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:24.040
this like very carefully, but like sometimes you have to ask for forgiveness instead of

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:29.520
permission, like no one's going to people might not be like, yeah, go use R and do

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:30.359
do this different thing.

00:17:30.359 --> 00:17:34.920
But if you can show them something really cool that you did in R and some capabilities

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:40.680
that you don't have in SAS, then that's what is going to get people excited about it.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:49.439
A conversation I would love to open up with the community here, because I see a lot I

00:17:49.439 --> 00:17:54.599
know you mentioned like Twitter was a great way for people to find out about new things

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:55.560
and new packages.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:59.599
And now a lot of our community isn't over there as often.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:05.439
And I just wanted to know, how do you keep up to date on new things now?

00:18:08.079 --> 00:18:16.079
So our weekly still runs, they used to actually have a mailing service where you would get

00:18:16.079 --> 00:18:20.400
the email with the weekly emails and that mailing service is down and has been down.

00:18:20.839 --> 00:18:26.880
But the curators are actually still working every week to curate content and like

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:28.880
aggregate all of those posts.

00:18:29.239 --> 00:18:33.719
So it's still a really good resource if you remember to go check it out yourself.

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:43.680
And then the other thing I do is I listen to Eric Nance, our podcast and Michael, because

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:49.680
they talk about the top three highlights from the R weekly posts, and they add like a really

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:55.719
nice layer of context and depth and conversation around those posts about their own personal

00:18:55.719 --> 00:18:56.640
experiences.

00:18:56.920 --> 00:18:59.400
And I think that's a really nice way to stay on top of something.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:02.640
Thank you.

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:05.959
Yeah, I'm curious to hear from everyone in the chat as well.

00:19:05.959 --> 00:19:08.599
I see a few other links being shared.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:12.560
But I was just wondering how people learn about new packages as well.

