I can't think necessarily about received, but we do have an intern right now at our group, and

00:19:52.479 --> 00:19:55.239
she's very lovely to work with, and I believe she is on this call.

00:19:55.880 --> 00:20:02.959
She is going to be graduating from college in the next year, and she's a little frazzled about what

00:20:02.959 --> 00:20:05.239
she's going to do for her first job.

00:20:05.599 --> 00:20:07.439
And I keep telling her to relax.

00:20:08.239 --> 00:20:12.040
It is your first job, and it's not going to be your forever job, right?

00:20:12.040 --> 00:20:14.160
Like, your career is about iteration.

00:20:14.359 --> 00:20:18.680
You're going to take what you get in your first job, and hopefully it's a good one.

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:23.199
But you're going to learn what you like to do, and you're going to learn what you don't like to

00:20:23.199 --> 00:20:25.520
do, and you're going to iterate and move on from there.

00:20:25.520 --> 00:20:29.959
And just because it's your first job, it doesn't necessarily lock you into that career path

00:20:29.959 --> 00:20:30.599
forever.

00:20:33.599 --> 00:20:34.239
I love that.

00:20:34.239 --> 00:20:34.880
Thank you.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:41.560
I see Neil asked a question a little bit earlier that was, could you give any leadership advice on

00:20:41.560 --> 00:20:47.160
how to bring people together and get a diverse range of views and ensure people are heard?

00:20:52.359 --> 00:20:58.359
Bringing people together and getting a diverse range of views is really about creating a very

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:02.680
safe place for people to talk, like a place like this.

00:21:03.199 --> 00:21:09.560
So, you need a safe environment, and that comes in a lot of different ways.

00:21:10.119 --> 00:21:15.239
There's quite a bit of infrastructure and thought that goes into creating that safe

00:21:15.239 --> 00:21:15.839
environment.

00:21:16.439 --> 00:21:21.880
So, for example, with Our Ladies, some things that we have are our code of conduct that

00:21:21.880 --> 00:21:28.199
explains, like, what sorts of behaviors, like, will not be tolerated in our events and other

00:21:28.199 --> 00:21:34.439
things that you can do to provide that infrastructure or provide suggestions or ways

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:39.000
that people can communicate in that environment, which Rachel does so good at here, right?

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:43.880
She tells you, you can drop questions in the chat, you can post questions anonymously, you

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:46.439
can star them if you want to read them yourself, right?

00:21:46.599 --> 00:21:50.160
It's really explicit how to interact in this environment.

00:21:50.319 --> 00:21:55.199
And the person on the other end of the call, like, doesn't have to guess about, like, what

00:21:55.199 --> 00:21:55.599
should I do?

00:21:55.599 --> 00:21:56.640
Am I going to go on camera?

00:21:56.640 --> 00:21:58.239
Like, what's the process here, right?

00:21:58.239 --> 00:22:00.199
There's no guesswork for that person.

00:22:00.199 --> 00:22:05.719
So, that, like, tension and trepidation that a person might feel about interacting in that

00:22:05.719 --> 00:22:08.599
environment is removed because you know exactly what to do.

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:14.079
So, I think when you are trying to build diverse communities, you need to set up that

00:22:14.079 --> 00:22:19.719
infrastructure to make people safe, but also to guide people on how to interact.

00:22:22.719 --> 00:22:23.560
Thank you, Shannon.

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:29.920
And thank you for, I mean, I was looking back on LinkedIn in 2021 when we were talking

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:35.719
about the Data Science Hangout and how to make sure it was welcoming and inclusive.

00:22:35.719 --> 00:22:40.520
And I remember you and I and I think Libby got on a chat and we're just kind of going

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:44.040
through some ideas and just brainstorming with each other.

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:46.520
And I really appreciate that.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:49.680
And I can't believe how much time has passed from that.

00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:56.680
But I just wanted to share that out with the community, too, if you are hoping to start

00:22:56.680 --> 00:23:02.959
your own group or just kind of want to float some ideas past someone here, you can

00:23:02.959 --> 00:23:09.160
always reach out to me about how to make sure that things are welcoming and inclusive.

00:23:09.479 --> 00:23:14.280
It's definitely an iterative process in the beginning to just make sure that you're

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:18.520
addressing all these different ways to have people interact.

00:23:19.920 --> 00:23:21.920
Yeah, just wanted to add that.

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:28.839
I see Kylie just asked a question in the chat, do you want to jump in?

00:23:29.719 --> 00:23:30.719
Yeah, sure, thanks.

00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:36.560
Hi, Shannon, I'm also a fellow co-organizer of Our Ladies, so just the Amsterdam

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:38.359
chapter. It's a bit later in the day for me.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:44.319
But I was actually interested in asking you a bit about something you said much earlier

00:23:44.319 --> 00:23:48.719
on about how you're now on clinical trials and that's your happy place and you were a

00:23:48.719 --> 00:23:51.199
professor for a while and then you were in market research.

00:23:51.199 --> 00:23:56.199
And I'm just kind of wondering how did you, one, decide to switch between those very

00:23:56.199 --> 00:23:59.439
different sectors and then also how you navigated it?

00:24:01.239 --> 00:24:11.239
Yeah, I mean, when I left teaching and it was like two factor decision, one that I had

00:24:11.239 --> 00:24:18.520
to relocate to be closer to my family, and I actually like really loved the department.

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:23.479
I was teaching and I feel like the best place in the world is like an undergraduate

00:24:23.479 --> 00:24:28.199
statistics program that truly cares deeply about teaching and teaching well.

00:24:28.199 --> 00:24:29.439
And I had so much fun there.

00:24:30.119 --> 00:24:34.119
But I also explained earlier that I was a little frustrated that I wasn't doing my own

00:24:34.119 --> 00:24:35.319
data science problems.

00:24:35.319 --> 00:24:37.199
I wasn't advancing my own data science knowledge.

00:24:37.199 --> 00:24:40.400
I felt like I was further behind than my students in programming and R.

00:24:42.280 --> 00:24:47.079
And so I decided when it was time to move, if I couldn't teach in the best place that I

00:24:47.079 --> 00:24:50.119
thought was the best place in the world, I was not going to teach anymore.

00:24:51.079 --> 00:24:55.359
And so and I needed to advance my own skill set.

00:24:56.760 --> 00:25:03.160
And so the first position I took in market research was like a really nice fit for me to

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:09.319
learn more about industry and how things operate outside of the academic world.

00:25:09.319 --> 00:25:16.520
It was different, you know, but it wasn't quite my favorite flavor of science.

00:25:17.239 --> 00:25:23.000
And I realized I kind of missed that more rigorous environment.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:29.319
And that's so that's why I'm so glad I ended up in clinical trials because it blends what

00:25:29.880 --> 00:25:33.959
like and pushing the edge of what you can do on data science, but also has that like nice,

00:25:33.959 --> 00:25:35.400
rigorous environment to it as well.

00:25:38.199 --> 00:25:40.680
And then if I may, can I ask a follow up question?

00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:41.079
Of course.

00:25:41.079 --> 00:25:41.640
Yeah.

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:46.760
So then I have also recently I saw that at the Posit Conf that there's going to be this

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:51.319
summit about open source and pharmaceutical companies.

00:25:51.319 --> 00:25:55.000
And I always thought that those two may not go hand in hand.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:02.920
So I am curious about sort of how you use open source tools like R and R packages and

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:11.000
things like that in a environment that needs to be very sort of closed and secure and sort

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
of how that those two are balanced.

00:26:13.640 --> 00:26:14.119
Yeah.

00:26:14.119 --> 00:26:19.800
I mean, I'm super lucky that the team I came into like it's a brand new team and didn't

00:26:19.800 --> 00:26:26.119
exist before, which means that there was like no legacy code existing like to protect.

00:26:26.119 --> 00:26:26.439
Right.

00:26:26.439 --> 00:26:28.760
So we were a brand new team.

00:26:28.760 --> 00:26:33.479
We were writing code from scratch, which meant like we could choose our own tool set and

00:26:33.479 --> 00:26:37.319
our tool set of choice was R and that was clear, you know, that that's the direction

00:26:37.319 --> 00:26:38.199
that we were going.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:45.560
As far as like industry standards, like it is accepted now that you can do R programming

00:26:46.520 --> 00:26:47.719
in clinical trials.

00:26:47.719 --> 00:26:48.280
Right.

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:53.239
But that's that's not the pushback or the barrier as much the pushback or the barrier

00:26:53.239 --> 00:27:00.920
is that like like a large portion of the industry is trained in SAS and a large portion of the

00:27:00.920 --> 00:27:07.079
pharmaceutical companies have a ton of existing framework built upon SAS macros.

00:27:07.079 --> 00:27:07.560
Right.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:12.760
So that is like really hard inertia to change both the training and the technical

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:13.479
infrastructure.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:20.359
But you'll see that a lot of larger pharmaceutical companies are have their own entire

00:27:20.359 --> 00:27:25.640
software engineering teams now where their jobs are to build R packages for internal

00:27:25.640 --> 00:27:28.920
processes to make that technical transition easier.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:35.479
And so a lot of the pharmaceutical companies are moving in that direction towards are at

00:27:35.479 --> 00:27:36.839
least trying to move the needle.

00:27:37.560 --> 00:27:41.800
So, thanks.

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:49.880
And Kylie, I shared a link in the chat, which might be helpful, but it has some cool pharma

00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:52.119
customer stories there as well.

00:27:52.760 --> 00:27:53.239
Oh, cool.

00:27:53.239 --> 00:27:53.560
Thanks.

00:27:53.560 --> 00:27:55.160
I'll go and find it.

00:27:55.959 --> 00:27:56.520
Absolutely.

00:27:58.359 --> 00:28:04.119
Okay, let me double check any questions I'm missing in the chat.

00:28:04.119 --> 00:28:08.920
I love seeing the conversations happen, but sometimes I lose the questions there.

00:28:12.199 --> 00:28:17.319
Shannon, I know I think it was your blog post last year where you did like a year

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:23.239
summary and you mentioned moving into more of a managerial role.

00:28:24.520 --> 00:28:30.439
Can you tell us about some of the lessons learned in moving into that managerial role

00:28:30.439 --> 00:28:32.520
that you share with some new managers here?

00:28:32.760 --> 00:28:33.239
Sure.

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:42.680
So, I was more at first like an individual contributor, just writing my own code, and

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:47.079
then our team grew, and then I had one direct report, and it grew again, and I had two direct

00:28:47.079 --> 00:28:50.119
reports, and it grew again, and I had three direct reports.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:57.079
And then all of a sudden, I was in a place where I found that I might have been giving

00:28:58.040 --> 00:29:06.280
the same feedback individually to the three direct reports instead of having a cohesive

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:13.959
place where I documented my expectations and made those clear upfront.

00:29:13.959 --> 00:29:20.839
So, that was something that I had to move towards to make sure, and it probably wasn't

00:29:20.839 --> 00:29:25.479
a something I could have done in the beginning because I didn't know what my expectations

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:25.880
were.

00:29:25.880 --> 00:29:29.479
And specifically, this is around code review and code submission.

00:29:29.479 --> 00:29:37.479
So, part of my managerial role is that the new contributors will submit code and submit

00:29:37.479 --> 00:29:41.719
pull requests, and I'm looking for two different things in that code.

00:29:41.719 --> 00:29:47.719
I'm first looking like does the code actually do what it needs to do, which is one question.

00:29:48.359 --> 00:29:54.599
But sometimes part of the harder question is did the code think about the data correctly?

00:29:55.160 --> 00:30:00.119
And in that sense, what I mean is that when you work with clinical trials data, like our

00:30:00.119 --> 00:30:07.560
data comes to us in a relational database type format with like 90 different data sets.

00:30:08.439 --> 00:30:14.680
And so, there's a lot of nuance in understanding how the data capture works, and that takes

00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:16.599
experience to get used to.

00:30:17.239 --> 00:30:22.920
So, it's not just like did your code work right, but like did you bring in the appropriate

00:30:22.920 --> 00:30:26.280
data from the appropriate data sets to make this conclusion?

00:30:28.119 --> 00:30:33.160
And so, I'm reviewing a lot of code, and I was giving feedback individually, and then

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:37.640
I realized I'm giving the same feedback over and over again, and I've got to document this

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:38.520
to make it clear.

00:30:38.520 --> 00:30:44.119
And I think once I did that, people were like oh my gosh, you told me, and now I understand.

00:30:44.119 --> 00:30:47.479
Like now that I've seen it all written out, like this makes sense.

00:30:47.479 --> 00:30:48.280
Thank you.

00:30:48.839 --> 00:30:54.199
I know code review is something we kind of like went off on a few weeks ago, and there

00:30:54.199 --> 00:30:56.839
was like a mission on the code review.

00:30:57.719 --> 00:30:58.219
Okay.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:02.520
So, I don't know if anyone had any follow-up questions based on that, too.

00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:04.920
What was the cliff notes from that?

00:31:07.319 --> 00:31:10.760
I will have to go get those resources shared.

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:16.119
I mean, I think code review is like such a big part of it, but I don't know if there's

00:31:16.119 --> 00:31:17.479
anything else you want to add to that.

00:31:17.479 --> 00:31:23.000
Yeah, I think code review is like such an interesting thing, because there's like this

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:28.920
very traditional context of code review in software engineering, where you're like writing

00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:33.239
functions for packages, you're doing unit tests, you're making sure the code does exactly

00:31:33.239 --> 00:31:37.560
what it says it's going to do, but that's like not the type of code review that I do.

00:31:37.560 --> 00:31:42.920
Like we're doing code review for data analysis, and I think that's a much different flavor

00:31:43.079 --> 00:31:49.719
documentation available, and I actually, I made my thoughts on it public on GitHub.

00:31:50.520 --> 00:31:55.079
If one of my friends on the call right now wants to go find that link and drop it in,

00:31:55.079 --> 00:31:55.959
that would be great.

00:31:57.719 --> 00:32:02.920
And you're welcome to read it, look through my thoughts, contribute anything back, and

00:32:02.920 --> 00:32:08.599
I made it public because I think it's, some of the things are kind of like still kind

00:32:08.599 --> 00:32:13.319
of internal to our team, but some of the things I think can more broadly apply to other

00:32:13.319 --> 00:32:18.359
teams, and I put it in a GitHub repo and not a blog post because I feel like it's going

00:32:18.359 --> 00:32:23.479
to be changing and evolving as I continue to think about it, and I also would love like

00:32:23.479 --> 00:32:25.000
other people's feedback on it.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:25.800
Thank you, Megan.

00:32:29.479 --> 00:32:29.959
Thank you.

00:32:30.839 --> 00:32:35.319
Laura, I see you mentioned you're interested in high-level code review tips.

00:32:36.119 --> 00:32:39.880
Do you want to jump in and share any context or introduce yourself?

00:32:41.079 --> 00:32:48.280
Yeah, no, I was just, you know, listening in, and I heard Shannon mention that that's

00:32:48.280 --> 00:32:50.920
specifically sort of what she was focusing in on.

00:32:50.920 --> 00:33:00.439
I have a survey, I taught myself R, and in the process of teaching myself R, and I'm

00:33:00.439 --> 00:33:08.280
trying to help a colleague just review some of her code for a survey analysis that we're

00:33:08.280 --> 00:33:08.520
doing.

00:33:08.520 --> 00:33:12.520
So, we're like, you know, coalescing the data, cleaning the data, and then we're going

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:18.359
to be doing the analysis and then report output from all from R.

00:33:20.359 --> 00:33:24.680
So, I do see the link that Shannon's colleague put in there, so I'm going to check that out,

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:31.719
but yeah, if you have any other sort of like high-level tips, that would be useful.

00:33:32.439 --> 00:33:35.160
There's maybe a better way to ask that, but that's, you know.

00:33:36.439 --> 00:33:43.560
No, I mean, I think when you're working in a team on code, you kind of have to have,

00:33:44.599 --> 00:33:48.280
especially if you're working long-term, or like, I don't know if this is a one-off

00:33:48.280 --> 00:33:53.959
project or not, but like you kind of have to hone in on like what your preferred style

00:33:53.959 --> 00:34:01.000
of coding is so that we can all read the code independently and smoothly without having

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.800
to guess what's going on, kind of have things in the same order and lining up.

00:34:07.800 --> 00:34:16.040
But in terms of like tips for code review, maybe I can work on that more.

00:34:16.040 --> 00:34:22.520
I mean, one of my goals over the next year is going to be for me to do less code review

00:34:22.520 --> 00:34:27.479
and for my direct reports to be doing more code review of each other and me so that they

00:34:27.479 --> 00:34:32.919
flip the role, and I think as we do that conversation, we'll learn more about like

00:34:33.879 --> 00:34:36.360
processes about what works for everyone in terms of it.

00:34:36.360 --> 00:34:43.800
But it's a pretty painstaking process, to be honest, to go through everything line by line

00:34:44.439 --> 00:34:52.120
and validate the results as well to make sure that the tables are coming out right,

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:57.239
that the numbers are lining up, but it has to be done.

00:34:57.879 --> 00:34:59.399
Yeah, I'm feeling that.

00:34:59.399 --> 00:35:05.399
It is very painstaking, and this is a one-off project, and we are a new team,

00:35:05.399 --> 00:35:11.159
and we are starting to build our capabilities, and so I'm trying to also get more familiar

00:35:11.159 --> 00:35:16.679
with GitHub so we can work as a team in that space as things move on and evolve.

00:35:17.639 --> 00:35:22.840
Yeah, I'll have to follow you as you evolve that information as well.

00:35:23.959 --> 00:35:29.879
My initial tip, because you mentioned it, would then be allocate a lot of time,

00:35:29.879 --> 00:35:37.560
because it takes more time than you think, and probably as much or I'm not even sure what

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:40.919
fraction, but possibly as much time as it took that person to write the code.

00:35:41.719 --> 00:35:42.040
Okay.

00:35:43.800 --> 00:35:44.120
All right.

00:35:44.120 --> 00:35:44.919
I appreciate that.

00:35:44.919 --> 00:35:45.239
Thank you.

00:35:47.080 --> 00:35:47.479
Thank you.

00:35:48.280 --> 00:35:53.479
Libby, I see you asked a question a bit earlier around the R community.

00:35:53.479 --> 00:35:54.280
Do you want to jump in?

00:35:56.280 --> 00:35:56.760
Sure.

00:35:56.760 --> 00:36:02.040
I lost it, but it was definitely like how has being active in the community

00:36:02.840 --> 00:36:07.560
changed your trajectory, do you think, or opened up opportunities for you?

00:36:07.560 --> 00:36:12.520
I'm often talking to people who are very, very hesitant to start interacting in the

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:16.280
community or start posting things or just start talking about what they know,

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:19.719
and I wish that I could give them an example of an experience like,

00:36:19.719 --> 00:36:22.040
look, this is how expansive it could be for you.

00:36:22.040 --> 00:36:24.040
It is so expansive.

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:24.280
Yeah.

00:36:25.080 --> 00:36:27.080
I would say there's immense...

00:36:28.040 --> 00:36:34.199
I mean, you put in the investment when you do start interacting with the community,

00:36:34.199 --> 00:36:38.679
and it's hard and it's scary, but the returns on it are so immense, right?

00:36:41.239 --> 00:36:45.639
Previously, before I started blogging, or maybe even initially when I started blogging,

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:53.000
I felt like I had to figure everything out by myself, and I would just spend hours googling

00:36:53.000 --> 00:37:00.679
things and being kind of unhappy and chasing dead ends and not getting the answer to my

00:37:00.679 --> 00:37:02.520
questions and being frustrated.

00:37:03.239 --> 00:37:09.000
And then when you're part of a community, you can just ask for help and skip that eight

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:11.959
hours, and you can get help pretty fast.

00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:18.360
So there's huge time savings there, and it's fun, and you get to learn what other people's

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:20.040
areas of expertise are.

00:37:21.159 --> 00:37:21.959
So that's huge.

00:37:26.760 --> 00:37:30.040
Azuka had asked a question in the chat a little bit earlier.

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:35.080
It was, do you think there's a difference between a data scientist, data analyst, and

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:36.040
a statistician?

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:42.760
If a new grad asked you what they should major in for an MS program, which would you advise

00:37:42.760 --> 00:37:43.320
them towards?

00:37:47.239 --> 00:37:47.719
Yes.

00:37:49.800 --> 00:37:51.639
The data analyst one's kind of hard, right?

00:37:51.639 --> 00:38:00.280
Data scientist, statistician, I can parse out a little bit more easily that I used to

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:03.000
be a statistician, and now I'm a data scientist.

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:09.959
And part of that is I no longer want to compute p-values as part of my work, so I don't do

00:38:09.959 --> 00:38:10.520
that anymore.

00:38:11.239 --> 00:38:16.679
I think it was great training for me in that I understand how to think about data, and

00:38:16.679 --> 00:38:22.360
I know how data should be organized, but I'm not actually interested in doing the analysis

00:38:23.959 --> 00:38:26.120
or the heavy lifting of the analysis.

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:35.560
So if you really like doing the analysis and finding the results, then statistics is a

00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:36.679
great way to go.

00:38:38.199 --> 00:38:46.120
I think data science is obviously a very broad field and can mean a lot of things, but maybe

00:38:46.120 --> 00:38:55.080
to further delineate, you can do software engineering flavors of data science, and

00:38:56.040 --> 00:39:01.399
you can do more data analyst flavors of data science, and those are two different skill

00:39:01.399 --> 00:39:01.800
sets.

00:39:04.600 --> 00:39:11.080
So the people that I know that are software engineers, they have less opportunity to work

00:39:11.080 --> 00:39:15.239
with data and real-world problems.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:22.280
They're writing functions and tools to do things, and I do do some of that.

00:39:22.280 --> 00:39:27.320
I do do some package writing, but I would really miss working with the data.

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:29.159
I actually like working with data.

00:39:29.159 --> 00:39:34.760
I like working with real data, and I like finding the messes and helping find the solutions

00:39:34.760 --> 00:39:35.560
to the problems.

00:39:36.679 --> 00:39:44.199
So I think that's more of a data analyst role, and it might not have as fancy of a title

00:39:44.199 --> 00:39:49.639
or connotation, but I think it's still really fun and valuable work.

